      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA software used under a documented quality management system with version control, validation testing records, and change control procedures consistent with FDA 21 CFR Part 820.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2023 R1 is operated under DePuy Synthes QMS. Software validation records, installation qualification, and operational qualification documentation are on file. Version is locked for this COU; change control procedures prevent unauthorized updates during the assessment period."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems with known analytical solutions demonstrate correct implementation of the structural solver for beam bending and contact mechanics relevant to the COU.",
      "rationale": "Three NAFEMS benchmark problems (LE1, LE10, and a Hertzian contact patch test) were executed in Ansys Mechanical 2023 R1. All results agree with reference solutions within 1.5%, confirming correct solver implementation for the physics classes present in the F1717 model."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates QoI change of less than 2% between successive refinement levels; Richardson extrapolation applied to estimate discretization error.",
      "rationale": "Three mesh refinement levels (coarse 1.2 mm, medium 0.8 mm, fine 0.5 mm global element size at screw shank) were evaluated. Stiffness QoI changed by 1.1% between medium and fine meshes. Richardson extrapolation yields an estimated discretization error of 0.6% for the production mesh (0.8 mm). Accepted."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals monitored; force and displacement convergence criteria documented and met for all load steps.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson iterative solver employed with force convergence tolerance 0.1% and displacement convergence tolerance 0.5%. All 11 load-displacement analyses converged within 50 substeps. No divergence or excessive bisection events recorded."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model setup reviewed by an independent analyst; boundary conditions, load application, and material assignments verified against the simulation specification document.",
      "rationale": "An independent senior FEA engineer performed a documented peer review of the simulation specification and Ansys project file prior to production runs. Boundary condition application (fixed base plate, axial-bending load via superior fixture), material assignments, and contact definitions were verified. No discrepancies identified."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Constitutive model selection (bilinear isotropic hardening) is justified by literature and coupon testing; geometric simplifications documented and their effect on QoIs bounded.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening is well-established for Ti-6Al-4V under quasi-static monotonic loading and is consistent with ASTM F1717 test conditions. Thread geometry is represented via equivalent cross-sectional area approach, validated against full-thread models in prior internal studies showing less than 3% QoI impact. Model form uncertainty is included in the validation uncertainty budget."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All material and geometric inputs are traceable to measured data; input uncertainty is quantified and propagated to QoI uncertainty estimates.",
      "rationale": "Material property inputs (elastic modulus, yield strength, tangent modulus) are sourced from lot-specific coupon tensile testing (Dataset nagaraja-material-props-ds001). Geometric inputs are derived from CMM inspection reports for the production screw and rod lot. Input uncertainty is propagated via a one-at-a-time sensitivity analysis; combined input uncertainty contribution to stiffness QoI is estimated at ±2.3%. The material dataset vintage (2025-10-08) predates the model revision date (2025-11-03) by approximately 26 days; the revision addressed rod-to-screw interface surface finish tolerance tightening and was assessed by the modeling team as not materially affecting bulk constitutive properties, so no re-characterization was performed."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test constructs are representative of the production design; sample size is sufficient to characterize experimental variability for comparison with FEA predictions.",
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs assembled from production-released non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screws and 5.5 mm titanium rods. CMM inspection confirmed dimensional conformance. Sample size yields coefficient of variation below 8% for all three QoIs, providing adequate experimental uncertainty characterization for E/uval computation."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios or the single condition tested is demonstrated to be the worst-case or most representative scenario.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 load configuration (compression-bending, 10 mm offset). While this is the standard regulatory configuration, no additional load angles or offset distances were evaluated. The required credibility level of 2 is not achieved; this factor is documented as a known gap and accepted under the rationale that ASTM F1717 is the FDA-recognized consensus standard for this device class and the single condition is the regulatory worst-case benchmark."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model inputs are demonstrably equivalent to the physical test specimen parameters; any differences are quantified and their effect on QoIs is bounded.",
      "rationale": "FEA geometry was updated to match CMM-measured dimensions of the actual test lot (screw shank diameter, rod diameter, screw-rod offset). Material properties were taken from the same production lot as the test constructs. Torque applied to polyaxial screw heads during assembly was measured and applied as a pre-tension boundary condition in the model. Equivalency is confirmed; residual differences are included in the validation uncertainty budget."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (percent difference and E/uval) computed for all three QoIs; all values within pre-established acceptance bounds.",
      "rationale": "Stiffness: 4.2% difference, E/uval = 0.87. Yield force: 6.8% difference, E/uval = 1.21. Force at 40 mm: 5.1% difference, E/uval = 0.94. All three QoIs satisfy the pre-established bounds of <10% and E/uval < 1.96. Validation uncertainty includes experimental measurement uncertainty, model input uncertainty, and numerical solution uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly linked to the clinical risk of construct failure and are the quantities used in the regulatory submission.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness characterizes load transfer to the vertebral bodies; yield force defines the onset of permanent deformation; force at 40 mm displacement is the regulatory performance benchmark per ASTM F1717. All three are directly used in the 510(k) substantial equivalence argument. QoIs are fully relevant to the COU."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities are conducted on the same device design, material system, and loading configuration as the COU; any differences between the validation context and the COU are documented and bounded.",
      "rationale": "The validation constructs use the same non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw design, same rod diameter and material, and the same ASTM F1717 test configuration as the COU. Testing was performed at two independent laboratories, increasing confidence in result reproducibility. The validation activities are directly representative of the COU with no material differences identified."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-dr-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/depuy-synthes-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All 13 V&V 40 credibility factors assessed. Twelve of thirteen factors meet or exceed the required credibility level. The single shortfall (Test conditions, achieved level 1 vs. required level 2) is accepted under the rationale that ASTM F1717 is the FDA-recognized consensus standard defining the single regulatory benchmark condition for spinal implant constructs, and no additional loading configurations are required for the 510(k) submission. Quantitative validation metrics for all three QoIs satisfy pre-established acceptance bounds. The credibility assessment supports regulatory submission of the non-cannulated pedicle screw FEA results.",
